@node Introduction "Wipe Documentation - Introduction"

@{b}Wipe@{ub} is a secure deletion utility.

What this means is that any file that is 'Wiped' is over-written with garbage
before removal.

It works along similar lines to a program called NUKE which I used to use, but
it did not work with AmiFileSafe (you could un-delete the original file!), so
I decided to write my own and here it is.

@{b}Wipe@{ub} is Freeware.
@endnode

@node Requirements "Wipe Documentation - Requirements"

@{b}Wipe@{ub} requires OS 2.0 or higher to run.
@endnode

@node Installation "Wipe Documentation - Installation"

To install @{b}Wipe@{ub}, just copy it to your C: directory.
@endnode

@node Usage "Wipe Documentation - Usage"

You can use @{b}Wipe@{ub} either from Workbench or the Shell/CLI.

Workbench

  Simply click on the @{b}Wipe@{ub} icon and then extended double click
  on the file to Wipe (ie hold down shift and double click).

  Wipe will then ask if you want to really Wipe the file.

Shell/CLI

  Just use specify the name of the file to Wipe.

  Wipe will then ask if you really want to Wipe the file. Type Y followed by
  return to wipe it, anything else will abandon the wipe.

  An extra option - GUI - is available when run from the Shell/CLI. This turns
  on the Wipe requesters for errors/conformation if you prefer.
  (eg Wipe GUI Filename)
@endnode

@node Bugs "Wipe Documentation - Bugs"

There are no known bugs with @{b}Wipe@{ub} (Famous last words ... :),
but if you find one @{"drop me a line" link Author}.
@endnode

